%I A396047 #25 Jul 20 2026 17:01:00
%S A396047 218252837281,4327509877535533,4720802756843862,8332191823007191
%N A396047 Integers k with 2*m digits such that the product of the number formed by the first m digits and the number formed by the last m digits equals the reversal of k.
%C A396047 If k is any integer with 2*m digits, where p is the number formed by the first m digits and q is the number formed by the last m digits, then it is not possible for p*q to equal k, since p*q < k, but it is possible for p*q = reversal(k). This list compiles these values of k. Furthermore, p and q necessarily have the same number of digits. In particular, q cannot start with 0.
%C A396047 The smallest number with this property is 218252837281, since splitting it in half yields the numbers 218252 and 837281, whose product is 182738252812, which is the reversal of 218252837281.
%C A396047 If k is a term, then k > reversal(k).
%C A396047 If p is the first block and q is the second block of k, then p*q == p + q (mod 9).
%C A396047 a(5) <= 65236640434475469192, a(6) <= 79907499718794337207. - _David A. Corneth_, Jul 14 2026
%e A396047        k          |       (p, q)          |  p*q = reversal(k)
%e A396047 __________________|_______________________|_____________________
%e A396047 218252837281      | (218252, 837281)      |  182738252812
%e A396047 4327509877535533  | (43275098, 77535533)  |  3355357789057234
%e A396047 4720802756843862  | (47208027, 56843862)  |  2683486572080274
%e A396047 8332191823007191  | (83321918, 23007191)  |  1917003281912338
%o A396047 (PARI) is(n) = {my(qd = #Str(n)); if(qd % 2 != 0, return(0)); my(pow10 = 10^(qd\2)); (n%pow10)*(n\pow10) == fromdigits(Vecrev(digits(n)))} \\ _David A. Corneth_, Jul 13 2026
%Y A396047 Cf. A009944, A004086.
%K A396047 nonn,base,more,new
%O A396047 1,1
